ResultCommentText:
#37
Prepared to collect from the bridge using pole sampler but the stream was too shallow at that point.  Went to the property owner's house at the top of the hill to ask permission to access the stream through the cattle gate like they had allowed previously. Ms. McClanahan phoned her husband (although I think it might have been her son) and gave me the phone.  I asked him if it would be OK to access the stream through the gate like we had previously and he said it would be OK.  We sampled the stream from at sycamore tree where the stream is free-flowing.
Water was fairly clear although there was a significant amount of algae present. Flow was pretty low.  Toward the end of sampling, the cow herd started coming toward us from the barn.  Mr. McClanahan rode down on his ATV and met us at the gate - cautioning us about one cow that might be a threat to us defending its calves.

ResultCommentText:
SURFACE

Sample collected at 0.5 meters using Van Dorn sampler

Orthophosphate result qualified due to blank contamination.

#37

We asked him if we could again access the stream through their cattle gate instead of from the bridge.  He said 'yes' and that doing so would be better than at the bridge under which three cattle were congregated.  We collected at the sycamore tree straight out from the gate.  Flow was elevated, but not high.  Water was murky.

ResultCommentText:
#37
Original plan was to collect from bridge right-of-way using a pole sampler.  There were cows under the bridge.  Property owner met us and, after a long conversation (fully documented in field notebook) he pointed us to a location on his property further upstream where the influence of his cattle was less evident.  At this location, where the stream featured grassy banks and mid-stream grassy clumps, the water was fairly clear and some small fish were observed.  The very high DO caught our attention.
